===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|dum|nl}} {{term|sijn|lang=dum}}, from {{etyl|odt|nl}} {{term|sin|sīn|lang=odt}}. The infinitive along with the words {{term|is|lang=nl}}, {{term|zij|lang=nl}} and {{term||zijn|lang=nl}} (present indicative and subjunctive) derive ultimately from {{etyl|ine-pro|nl}} {{recons|h₁es-||to be|lang=ine-pro}}, which had no separate infinitive in Germanic. The modern infinitive was probably back-formed in late Old Dutch from the first-person plural subjunctive {{term||sīn|we be|lang=odt}}, since this form had become identical to the infinitive in other verbs during the late Old Dutch period. Compare also German {{term|sein|lang=de}}, Low German {{term|sön|lang=nds}}.

The original infinitive survives in {{term|wezen|lang=nl}}, from {{etyl|dum|nl}} {{term|wesen|lang=dum}}, from {{etyl|odt|nl}} {{term|wesan|lang=odt}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|nl}} {{recons|wesanan|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{recons|h₂wes-||to reside|lang=ine-pro}}. All the forms with initial ''w-'' (imperative and past tense) derive from this root.

Finally, the forms {{term|ben|lang=nl}} and {{term|bent|lang=nl}} derive from {{etyl|gem-pro|nl}} {{recons|beunan||to be, to become|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{recons|bʰuH-||to become|lang=ine-pro}}, which survives only as relic forms in the West Germanic languages and not at all in the others. Its infinitive and non-singular forms are only attested in (Old) English.

====Verb====
{{nl-verb}}

# {{intransitive|lang=nl}} To [[be]], to [[exist]].
#: {{lang|nl|'''''Zijn''' of niet '''zijn''', dat is de vraag.''}}
#:: To '''be''' or not to '''be''', that is the question.
#: {{lang|nl|'''''Was''' je er afgelopen zaterdag ook?''}}
#:: '''Were''' you there too last Saturday?
# {{transitive|copular|lang=nl}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to connect a noun to an adjective that describes it.}}
#: {{lang|nl|''De bal '''is''' rond.''}}
#:: The ball '''is''' round.
# {{transitive|auxiliary|lang=nl}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to form the [[perfect tense]] of the [[active voice]] of some verbs, together with a [[past participle]].<br/>'''Note:''' The perfect tense of most other verbs is formed using [[hebben]].}}
#: {{lang|nl|''Hij '''is''' hier geweest.''}}
#:: He '''has''' been here.
# {{transitive|auxiliary|lang=nl}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to form the [[perfect tense]] of the [[passive voice]], together with a [[past participle]].<br/>'''Note:''' The [[imperfect tense]] passive is formed using [[worden]].}}
#: {{lang|nl|''Ze '''waren''' gered.''}}
#:: They '''had been''' saved.
#: {{lang|nl|''De muur '''is''' geschilderd.''}}
#:: The wall '''has been''' painted.
#: {{lang|nl|''De muur zal '''zijn''' geschilderd.''}}
#:: The wall will '''have been''' painted.
# {{transitive|auxiliary|lang=nl}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to form the continuous forms of various tenses, together with '''[[aan het]]'''.}}
#: {{lang|nl|''De man '''was''' aan het lopen.''}}
#:: The man '''was''' walking.
# {{intransitive|lang=nl}} To [[go]], to go on a [[trip]] and return.
#: {{lang|nl|''Ik '''ben''' even naar de dokter.''}}
#:: I '''am going''' to the doctor for a while.
#: {{lang|nl|''Ik ben vandaag naar het strand '''geweest.'''}}
#:: I've '''been''' to the beach today.
# {{intransitive|impersonal|lang=nl}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate weather, temperature or some other general condition.}}
#: {{lang|nl|''Het '''is''' erg warm vandaag.''}}
#:: It '''is''' very warm today.
# {{transitive|copular|mathematics|lang=nl}} To [[equal]]; {{non-gloss definition|used to indicate that the values on either side of an equation are the same.}}
#: {{lang|nl|''Drie keer vijf '''is''' vijftien.''}}
#:: Three times five '''equals''' fifteen.
# {{intransitive|lang=nl}} To have the next [[turn]] in a [[game]].
#: {{lang|nl|''Jij '''bent''' nu.''}}
#:: It '''is your turn''' now.

