===Etymology 2===
From {{etyl|odt|nl}} {{term|sin|sīn|lang=odt}} (originally a reflexive form), from {{etyl|gem-pro|nl}} {{recons|sīnaz|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|nl}} {{recons|seyno-|lang=ine-pro}}. Cognate with German {{term|sein|lang=de}}, Swedish {{term|sin|lang=sv}}. Ultimately a form of the Proto-Indo-European reflexive pronoun {{recons|swe|lang=ine-pro}}, related to Russian {{term|себя|tr=sebja|lang=ru}}, Latin {{term|suus|lang=la}}, Ancient Greek {{term|ἑός|tr=heos|lang=grc}}, Sanskrit {{term|tr=sva|lang=sa}}{{rfscript|Deva}} etc.

